<paragraph blockId="8.[151,1437,1333,2043]" pageId="8" pageNumber="285">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,456,1333,1359]" pageId="8" pageNumber="285">Supplemental description</emphasis>
(based on non-type specimens examined for this study). Body length, male 6.50, female 5.80; maximum width, male 2.20, female 2.10. Anterior third of head, anterolateral region and posterior band of pronotum, parts of thoracic pleura, lateral region (just below impressed furrows) of abdominal sterna II–VII in male and II–VI in female covered by minute, frosty pubescence (as in 
<figureCitation box="[828,910,1441,1467]" captionStart="FIGURES 21–29" captionStartId="9.[151,264,1745,1769]" captionTargetBox="[152,1434,489,1721]" captionTargetId="figure-148@9.[151,1436,489,1722]" captionTargetPageId="9" captionText="FIGURES 21–29. Paravelia spp., (21–26) Paravelia nieseri Moreira &amp; Barbosa, (21) dorsal habitus of female from Serra do Caraça, Brazil (MZUSP), (22) dorsal view of head, (23) fore tibia of male, (24) fore tibia of female, (25) middle tibia of male, black arrow indicates elongate dark-brown trichobothria-like setae, (26) lateral view of female abdomen. (27–29) Paravelia rotundanotata (Hungerford), (27) dorsal habitus of micropterous male from Paragominas, Brazil (CEIOC), (28) fore tibia and tarsus of male, (29) lateral view of male abdomen. gc = grasping comb, if = impressed furrow, iml = impressed median line, cil = convergent impressed line, pi = posterior indentation, II–VII = abdominal segments." pageId="8" pageNumber="285">Fig. 22</figureCitation>
), visible mainly in posterior view. Ocular setae present. Posterior region of head with a pair of narrow, convergent, impressed lines between impressed median line and rounded posterior indentations (
<figureCitation box="[559,644,1513,1539]" captionStart="FIGURES 21–29" captionStartId="9.[151,264,1745,1769]" captionTargetBox="[152,1434,489,1721]" captionTargetId="figure-148@9.[151,1436,489,1722]" captionTargetPageId="9" captionText="FIGURES 21–29. Paravelia spp., (21–26) Paravelia nieseri Moreira &amp; Barbosa, (21) dorsal habitus of female from Serra do Caraça, Brazil (MZUSP), (22) dorsal view of head, (23) fore tibia of male, (24) fore tibia of female, (25) middle tibia of male, black arrow indicates elongate dark-brown trichobothria-like setae, (26) lateral view of female abdomen. (27–29) Paravelia rotundanotata (Hungerford), (27) dorsal habitus of micropterous male from Paragominas, Brazil (CEIOC), (28) fore tibia and tarsus of male, (29) lateral view of male abdomen. gc = grasping comb, if = impressed furrow, iml = impressed median line, cil = convergent impressed line, pi = posterior indentation, II–VII = abdominal segments." pageId="8" pageNumber="285">Fig. 22</figureCitation>
). Metasternum with posterior margin convex. Pro- and mesoacetabula each with a rounded punctation on mesal surface. Male fore tibia (
<quantity box="[912,1015,1549,1576]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.75" pageId="8" pageNumber="285" unit="mm" value="1.75">1.75 mm</quantity>
long) with grasping comb (
<quantity box="[1333,1437,1549,1575]" metricMagnitude="-4" metricUnit="m" metricValue="9.6" pageId="8" pageNumber="285" unit="mm" value="0.96">0.96 mm</quantity>
long) occupying little more than half of its length (
<figureCitation box="[724,809,1585,1611]" captionStart="FIGURES 21–29" captionStartId="9.[151,264,1745,1769]" captionTargetBox="[152,1434,489,1721]" captionTargetId="figure-148@9.[151,1436,489,1722]" captionTargetPageId="9" captionText="FIGURES 21–29. Paravelia spp., (21–26) Paravelia nieseri Moreira &amp; Barbosa, (21) dorsal habitus of female from Serra do Caraça, Brazil (MZUSP), (22) dorsal view of head, (23) fore tibia of male, (24) fore tibia of female, (25) middle tibia of male, black arrow indicates elongate dark-brown trichobothria-like setae, (26) lateral view of female abdomen. (27–29) Paravelia rotundanotata (Hungerford), (27) dorsal habitus of micropterous male from Paragominas, Brazil (CEIOC), (28) fore tibia and tarsus of male, (29) lateral view of male abdomen. gc = grasping comb, if = impressed furrow, iml = impressed median line, cil = convergent impressed line, pi = posterior indentation, II–VII = abdominal segments." pageId="8" pageNumber="285">Fig. 23</figureCitation>
). Female fore tibia (
<quantity box="[1037,1139,1585,1611]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.44" pageId="8" pageNumber="285" unit="mm" value="1.44">1.44 mm</quantity>
long) with grasping comb (
<quantity box="[159,262,1621,1647]" metricMagnitude="-4" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.4" pageId="8" pageNumber="285" unit="mm" value="0.14">0.14 mm</quantity>
long) occupying only a small apical portion of segment (
<figureCitation box="[921,1008,1621,1647]" captionStart="FIGURES 21–29" captionStartId="9.[151,264,1745,1769]" captionTargetBox="[152,1434,489,1721]" captionTargetId="figure-148@9.[151,1436,489,1722]" captionTargetPageId="9" captionText="FIGURES 21–29. Paravelia spp., (21–26) Paravelia nieseri Moreira &amp; Barbosa, (21) dorsal habitus of female from Serra do Caraça, Brazil (MZUSP), (22) dorsal view of head, (23) fore tibia of male, (24) fore tibia of female, (25) middle tibia of male, black arrow indicates elongate dark-brown trichobothria-like setae, (26) lateral view of female abdomen. (27–29) Paravelia rotundanotata (Hungerford), (27) dorsal habitus of micropterous male from Paragominas, Brazil (CEIOC), (28) fore tibia and tarsus of male, (29) lateral view of male abdomen. gc = grasping comb, if = impressed furrow, iml = impressed median line, cil = convergent impressed line, pi = posterior indentation, II–VII = abdominal segments." pageId="8" pageNumber="285">Fig. 24</figureCitation>
). Middle tibia with a row of elongate dark-brown trichobothria-like setae on posterior third, decreasing in size distally (
<figureCitation box="[1089,1175,1657,1684]" captionStart="FIGURES 21–29" captionStartId="9.[151,264,1745,1769]" captionTargetBox="[152,1434,489,1721]" captionTargetId="figure-148@9.[151,1436,489,1722]" captionTargetPageId="9" captionText="FIGURES 21–29. Paravelia spp., (21–26) Paravelia nieseri Moreira &amp; Barbosa, (21) dorsal habitus of female from Serra do Caraça, Brazil (MZUSP), (22) dorsal view of head, (23) fore tibia of male, (24) fore tibia of female, (25) middle tibia of male, black arrow indicates elongate dark-brown trichobothria-like setae, (26) lateral view of female abdomen. (27–29) Paravelia rotundanotata (Hungerford), (27) dorsal habitus of micropterous male from Paragominas, Brazil (CEIOC), (28) fore tibia and tarsus of male, (29) lateral view of male abdomen. gc = grasping comb, if = impressed furrow, iml = impressed median line, cil = convergent impressed line, pi = posterior indentation, II–VII = abdominal segments." pageId="8" pageNumber="285">Fig. 25</figureCitation>
). Male hind trochanter with small, obtuse spines posteriorly. Abdomen laterally with roughly ovate to rounded impressed longitudinal furrows (
<figureCitation box="[221,305,1729,1755]" captionStart="FIGURES 21–29" captionStartId="9.[151,264,1745,1769]" captionTargetBox="[152,1434,489,1721]" captionTargetId="figure-148@9.[151,1436,489,1722]" captionTargetPageId="9" captionText="FIGURES 21–29. Paravelia spp., (21–26) Paravelia nieseri Moreira &amp; Barbosa, (21) dorsal habitus of female from Serra do Caraça, Brazil (MZUSP), (22) dorsal view of head, (23) fore tibia of male, (24) fore tibia of female, (25) middle tibia of male, black arrow indicates elongate dark-brown trichobothria-like setae, (26) lateral view of female abdomen. (27–29) Paravelia rotundanotata (Hungerford), (27) dorsal habitus of micropterous male from Paragominas, Brazil (CEIOC), (28) fore tibia and tarsus of male, (29) lateral view of male abdomen. gc = grasping comb, if = impressed furrow, iml = impressed median line, cil = convergent impressed line, pi = posterior indentation, II–VII = abdominal segments." pageId="8" pageNumber="285">Fig. 26</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="8" pageNumber="285" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="8.[151,1437,1333,2043]" pageId="8" pageNumber="285">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,332,1765,1791]" pageId="8" pageNumber="285">Discussion.</emphasis>
Illustrations of this species, as well as other diagnostic characteristics, were provided by 
<bibRefCitation author="Moreira, F. F. F. &amp; Barbosa, J. F." pageId="8" pageNumber="285" pagination="58 - 68" refId="ref6841" refString="Moreira, F. F. F. &amp; Barbosa, J. F. (2012) Two new species of Paravelia Breddin, 1898 and distributional notes concerning the Veliidae from Minas Gerais State, Brazil (Insecta: Hemiptera: Heteroptera: Gerromorpha). Zootaxa, 3354 (1), 58 - 68. https: // doi. org / 10.11646 / zootaxa. 3354.1.2" type="journal article" year="2012">Moreira &amp; Barbosa (2012)</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation author="Rodrigues, H. D. D. &amp; Moreira, F. F. F. &amp; Nieser, N. &amp; Chen, P. P. &amp; Melo, A. L. de &amp; Dias-Silva, K. &amp; Giehl, N. F. S." box="[367,630,1801,1827]" pageId="8" pageNumber="285" pagination="1 - 47" refId="ref7271" refString="Rodrigues, H. D. D., Moreira, F. F. F., Nieser, N., Chen, P. P., Melo, A. L. de, Dias-Silva, K. &amp; Giehl, N. F. S. (2014) The genus Paravelia Breddin, 1898 (Hemiptera: Heteroptera: Veliidae) in Brazil, with descriptions of eight new species. Zootaxa, 3784 (1), 1 - 47. https: // doi. org / 10.11646 / zootaxa. 3784.1.1" type="journal article" year="2014">
Rodrigues 
<emphasis box="[489,539,1801,1827]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="285">et al</emphasis>
. (2014)
</bibRefCitation>
, and 
<bibRefCitation author="Rodrigues, J. M. S. &amp; Moreira, F. F. F." box="[688,1014,1801,1827]" pageId="8" pageNumber="285" pagination="1 - 17" refId="ref7371" refString="Rodrigues, J. M. S. &amp; Moreira, F. F. F. (2022) New species, new records, and updated key to the Paravelia (Hemiptera: Heteroptera: Veliidae) from Brazil. Insects, 13 (541), 1 - 17. https: // doi. org / 10.3390 / insects 13060541" type="journal article" year="2022">Rodrigues &amp; Moreira (2022)</bibRefCitation>
. 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Moreira &amp; Barbosa" authorityYear="2012" box="[1025,1218,1801,1827]" class="Insecta" family="Veliidae" genus="Paravelia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="8" pageNumber="285" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="nieseri">
<emphasis box="[1025,1218,1801,1827]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="285">Paravelia nieseri</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is morphologically very similar to 
<taxonomicName authority="Polhemus &amp; Polhemus, 1985" authorityName="Polhemus &amp; Polhemus" authorityYear="1985" box="[321,760,1837,1864]" class="Insecta" family="Veliidae" genus="Paravelia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="8" pageNumber="285" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="truxali">
<emphasis box="[321,424,1837,1863]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="285">P. truxali</emphasis>
Polhemus &amp; Polhemus, 1985
</taxonomicName>
, and both can be separated by the color of the pronotum and the structure of the female hind femur. In 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Moreira &amp; Barbosa" authorityYear="2012" box="[634,739,1874,1899]" class="Insecta" family="Veliidae" genus="Paravelia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="8" pageNumber="285" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="nieseri">
<emphasis box="[634,739,1874,1899]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="285">P. nieseri</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, the pronotum is mostly black with only an orange posterior band (
<figureCitation box="[222,304,1909,1935]" captionStart="FIGURES 21–29" captionStartId="9.[151,264,1745,1769]" captionTargetBox="[152,1434,489,1721]" captionTargetId="figure-148@9.[151,1436,489,1722]" captionTargetPageId="9" captionText="FIGURES 21–29. Paravelia spp., (21–26) Paravelia nieseri Moreira &amp; Barbosa, (21) dorsal habitus of female from Serra do Caraça, Brazil (MZUSP), (22) dorsal view of head, (23) fore tibia of male, (24) fore tibia of female, (25) middle tibia of male, black arrow indicates elongate dark-brown trichobothria-like setae, (26) lateral view of female abdomen. (27–29) Paravelia rotundanotata (Hungerford), (27) dorsal habitus of micropterous male from Paragominas, Brazil (CEIOC), (28) fore tibia and tarsus of male, (29) lateral view of male abdomen. gc = grasping comb, if = impressed furrow, iml = impressed median line, cil = convergent impressed line, pi = posterior indentation, II–VII = abdominal segments." pageId="8" pageNumber="285">Fig. 21</figureCitation>
) and the female hind femur lacks black pegs, whereas in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Polhemus &amp; Polhemus" authorityYear="1985" box="[957,1060,1909,1935]" class="Insecta" family="Veliidae" genus="Paravelia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="8" pageNumber="285" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="truxali">
<emphasis box="[957,1060,1909,1935]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="285">P. truxali</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
the pronotum is orange, with the anterior lobe, humeral angles, and a wide median stripe black, and the female hind femur has seven black pegs on the posterior surface, which increase in size distally.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection lastPageId="9" lastPageNumber="286" pageId="8" pageNumber="285" type="distribution">
<paragraph blockId="8.[151,1437,1333,2043]" lastBlockId="9.[151,1437,150,465]" lastPageId="9" lastPageNumber="286" pageId="8" pageNumber="285">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,497,2017,2043]" pageId="8" pageNumber="285">Distribution and habitat.</emphasis>
This species is distributed in the States of 
<collectingRegion box="[974,1123,2017,2043]" country="Brazil" name="Minas Gerais" pageId="8" pageNumber="285">Minas Gerais</collectingRegion>
and 
<collectingRegion box="[1178,1238,2017,2043]" country="Brazil" name="Piaui" pageId="8" pageNumber="285">Piauí</collectingRegion>
, southeastern and northeastern 
<collectingCountry box="[298,366,151,177]" name="Brazil" pageId="9" pageNumber="286">Brazil</collectingCountry>
respectively, in regions ranging from 524 to 1300 meters in elevation (
<figureCitation box="[1179,1264,151,177]" captionStart="FIGURE 30" captionStartId="10.[151,250,1975,1999]" captionTargetBox="[298,1290,982,1951]" captionTargetId="figure-292@10.[298,1290,982,1951]" captionTargetPageId="10" captionText="FIGURE 30. Distribution records of five species of Paravelia in South America." pageId="9" pageNumber="286">Fig. 30</figureCitation>
). It can be collected in temporary ponds on open trails, in ponds in shaded areas with litter substrate, and more recently, it has been found in subterranean waters in limestone caves.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="9.[151,1437,150,465]" pageId="9" pageNumber="286">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,420,258,285]" pageId="9" pageNumber="286">Published records.</emphasis>
<collectingCountry box="[425,498,259,285]" name="Brazil" pageId="9" pageNumber="286">Brazil</collectingCountry>
: 
